A black box in the car?
U.S. road planners are looking for a source of money to repair the falling highway system, believing they have found the solution in a small black box that can be placed in the dashboard of each car.
The devices that record every mile traveled and report the information to the authorities are at the heart of a controversial attempt by Washington and the U.S. state planning agencies to revise the outdated system for funding U.S. roads.
The usually rather boring area of road planning has suddenly sparked an intense debate with colourful alliances.
Libertarians have allied with environmental groups and are advocating that the government can use the small boxes to record the miles driven – and possibly where they were driven – and then use the information to calculate tax reductions.
The tea party is terrible.
The American Civil Rights Association (ACLU) is also deeply concerned and expresses a number of data protection concerns.
But while you can’t agree on a move in Congress, several states don’t wait any longer.
They are currently considering how they can switch over the next ten years to a system where drivers pay per mile driven.
Thousands of drivers have already tested the driving screens, some of which are equipped with GPS monitoring.
This is a must for our country.
“It’s nothing we’re just going to potentially use,” said Hasan Ikhrata, managing director of Southern California Assn. of Governments, which plans to record miles driven by all California drivers in the state from 2025.
The way we pay these taxes will change.
The technology for that is there.
The initiative comes at a time when the Highway Trust Fund, which is funded from the taxes Americans pay on the pillar, is bankrupt.
In America, however, there is no longer as much dance as it used to be.
Cars use less gasoline.
The state mineral oil tax of 18.4 cents per gallon (less than 4 eurocents per liter) has not increased for 20 years.
With high alcohol prices, politicians do not dare to raise the tax even by a penny.
“The gasoline tax is simply not sustainable,” said Lee Munnich, an expert on traffic legislation at the University of Minnesota.
Its state has recently equipped 500 cars with roadmaps to test a mile-based payment system.
“This is the most meaningful alternative in the long term,” he said.
Bureaucrats refer to it as a mile-based user fee.
It is not surprising that the idea is popular with urban liberals, as the tax could be used, for example, to influence driving behavior in a way that reduces congestion and climate-damaging emissions.
California planners rely on the system in developing strategies to the state’s ambitious, legally-enforced climate change goals.
But Republican Bill Shuster from Pennsylvania, chairman of the House Transportation Committee, has also stated that he sees it as the most common long-term alternative.
The free marketers of the Reason Foundation are also motivated by the idea of paying drivers after the journey.
“This is not a tax that disappears in a black hole,” said Adrian Moore, vice president of policy at Reason.
People pay directly for what they get.
The movement is also supported by two former U.S. transport ministers who, in a 2011 report, urged Congress to move towards mile-based billing.
Last year, the U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project involving 10,000 cars.
But the majority in the House of Representatives prevented the push, responding to concerns from MPs from rural areas, who represent people who often have to travel many miles on their way to work or into the city in their daily lives.
Nevertheless, several states and major cities are moving in this direction on their own.
The most committed is Oregon, which is currently hiring 5,000 drivers for the country’s largest experiment.
These drivers will soon pay the mileage fees instead of the mineral oil tax to the state.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is also considering this.
Illinois is testing it to a limited extent with trucks.
And the I-95 Coalition, which includes the transport ministries of 17 states on the East Coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia, and Florida), is currently exploring how to introduce the change.
The concept is not a universal hit.
In Nevada, where 50 volunteers were recently equipped with the devices, drivers were skeptical of the idea that the government could track each of their movements.
“Preoccupations about Big Brother and things like that were a big problem,” said Alauddin Khan, head of strategy and result management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
People did not want it.
When the test arrived, the ACLU of Nevada warned on its website: “It would be relatively easy to turn the driving recorders into adult surveillance devices.”
There is no need to build a gigantic, vast technological infrastructure that would inevitably be used to collect data on the daily movements of individuals.
Nevada is one of a number of states that are now looking for affordable technology that allows the state to record the miles travelled, but not exactly when and where.
This, according to Khan, would also make the public more calm.
The hunt for this technology has led some authorities to a small start-up company called True Mileage in California.
The company originally did not come up to help states tax car drivers.
Rather, their goal was to set foot in an emerging market for car insurance, where drivers should pay on the basis of miles travelled.
But the devices she tested are also interesting for street planners, as they don’t work with GPS and only provide limited information that is regularly uploaded via modem.
“People are more likely to participate if their speed and locations are not recorded,” said Ryan Morrison, Managing Director of True Mileage.
Major mistakes have been made in some of these public pilot programs.
There are much cheaper and less intrusive ways to implement this.
In Oregon, planners are experimenting with giving drivers a range of choices.
You can choose a device with or without GPS.
Or they don’t choose a device at all and instead pay a flat-rate fee based on the average miles driven by all the inhabitants of the state.
Other sites hope to sell the concept to a suspicious public by equipping the devices with more functions than with fewer.
In New York City, traffic officials want to develop a taxation device that will also allow parking fees to be paid, insurance will only need to be paid for miles taken, and speed data from other vehicles will be collected in real time, allowing drivers to avoid traffic jams.
“Drivers would be motivated to participate by the added value of the benefits the system offers,” says a city planning document.
However, some traffic planners wonder if all the talk about paying per mile isn’t just a huge distraction maneuver.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission for the San Francisco Bay Area, officials stated that Congress could solve the problem of the bankrupt Highway Trust Fund simply by raising fuel tax.
An additional one-time fee or an annual fee could be imposed on drivers of hybrid vehicles or other low-fuel vehicles, so that they also pay a fair share.
“There is no need for surgery if one aspirin is enough,” said Randy Rentschler, the head of legislation and public affairs at the European Commission.
