ESA Decides on Large Space Missions: Missions for Billions
Distant planets, gravitational waves, or black holes – experts from the European Space Agency must now agree on two major projects they want to launch in the coming years.
Thirty proposals were selected, five are still in the race.
The distant worlds.
Astronomers have found more than 1,000 planets near other stars.
Whether there is life on some of them, nobody knows.
The choice is difficult: Should we look for gravitational waves?
Would you like to explore the origin of the cosmos?
Or search for Earth-like planets and discover extraterrestrial life?
These questions are being asked by the European Space Agency (ESA).
For their "Cosmic Vision" program, they are looking for ideas for two large space projects that are designed to significantly advance research.
The budget for such "L-missions" is approximately one billion euros.
The launch is expected to be in 2028 and 2034.
In early September, the elite of European space research met in Paris to discuss proposals for such missions.
Thirty ideas were debated, five of which have now come to the closer election.
Numerous bodies review the proposals, followed by the researchers.
A final decision will be made by the Scientific Program Committee in the coming days.
In total, the ESA has selected four major questions to be answered by the missions of the Cosmic Vision program initiated in 2007.
What are the conditions for the formation of planets and life?
The precise processes of star formation from large gas clouds – and thus the formation of planets orbiting these stars – are still in the proverbial darkness.
A large infrared telescope in space could penetrate this darkness.
And if a star has planets, under what circumstances can there be life?
In order to address this question, in 2017 the Space Telescope "Cheops" will be launched, using which 500 already known planetary systems in our nearest environment will be studied more closely.
The possibilities are limited, but Cheops is a small mission with a budget of 150 million euros.
Using larger instruments, astronomers could image Earth-like planets and even analyze the composition of their atmospheres, thus looking for "biomarkers": gases that are considered to indicate biological activity.
How does the solar system work?
In the end, this question is also meant to provide an explanation of the conditions for the emergence of life.
An important role is played by the magnetic activity of a star and the interaction of its magnetic field and the particle radiation emanating from it with the planetary system.
In our solar system, these processes can be studied in an exemplary way.
With the "Solar Orbiter", the ESA has already approved a M-Class mission (where the budget is about half a billion euros) for this matter.
The spacecraft will launch in 2017 to monitor the surface and activity of the sun.
Jupiter and its moons are also of great interest to the researchers.
They want to find out what role the giant planet played in the evolution of the solar system.
This is the first of three L missions in the Cosmic Vision program.
The Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer spacecraft is expected to begin its journey in 2022.
Eight years later, it reaches Jupiter and will study the planet's atmosphere as well as the icy moons Europe, Kallisto and Ganymed.
What are the basic physical laws of the universe?
The universe offers many opportunities to study matter under extreme conditions and thus to investigate whether the natural laws we know are still valid there.
Per there are also deviations that could show the physicists the way to a new theory, under the roof of which all known natural laws can be united.
How did the universe form and what is it made up of?
13.7 billion years ago, our cosmos was formed by the Big Bang.
In addition to the matter we are familiar with, consisting of stars, planets and living beings like us, there is dark matter, whose gravity holds galaxies and clusters of galaxies together, and dark energy, whose action accelerates the expansion of the universe.
So far, the researchers do not know what physical laws were valid in the first second fractions of the Big Bang, nor what dark matter and dark energy consist of.
With "Euclid", the ESA has already authorized a M-mission, which is scheduled for launch in 2020.
With a special telescope, the probe is to study the distribution of matter in the universe across the sky for the first time, allowing conclusions on the nature of dark matter and dark energy.
Who can run the race
Of the 30 proposals, only two will remain at the end of the selection process.
The best chance of being approved as a L-mission has, according to many experts, "E-Lisa", a sophisticated concept for detecting gravitational waves.
Among them, physicists understand changes in the structure of space time, which Albert Einstein predicted almost 100 years ago.
They have not been proven to this day.
Elisa could do that, hopefully the scientists behind the project.
The mission will include a detector consisting of two or three probes that will be stationed in space.
It could also detect gravitational waves created by the Big Bang, and thus provide new insights into the origin of the cosmos.
Four other proposals are still competing for the second L mission: a large X-ray telescope called "Athena" to explore black holes, "Icy Planets", another mission to the outer planets of the solar system, "Prism", a mission to measure cosmic background radiation, and the "Exoplanet Finder" to track and study Earth-like planets.
Proposals for the return of samples from Mars, for the exploration of the moon, Venus and asteroids, as well as for solar physics have already been submitted.
