What happens to my email on the go?
E-mail is actually an electronic letter.
Was the design of the Internet service e-mail technically similar to that of conventional mail?
In the conception of early Internet services, the focus was on making communication possible.
Therefore, the basic technical protocols did not provide a stable foundation for an audible correspondence exchange.
Therefore, a traditional email is more like an open postcard than a sealed letter.
When the user "Anna" sends an email to "Benni", are the computers of the two directly connected?
In the first step, Anna’s email program or browser sends the email to the mail server of her service provider.
For example, if you have a Gmail account, it would be Google.
This mail server sends the content to the provider that Benni uses.
On the way, the mail can run over a number of other servers on the Internet.
Bennie can then call the content to his provider.
Are traditional emails being read on their way through the network?
Most emails are read several times on the go by software robots.
The provider of the sender usually checks whether the mail carries a malicious program as an attachment.
A virus check is also performed on the recipient systems.
Furthermore, the providers check whether it is an annoying and undesirable spam email, which is immediately deleted or at least sorted away into a spam folder.
Do the robots have another task?
In systems like Gmail, the robot also collects the information Google needs to place contextual advertising.
When Anna and Benni communicate via Gmail about their upcoming vacation trip, Google can hide corresponding links to vacation offers.
Do unfamiliar people read emails?
The likelihood that unauthorized persons will read an email is extremely low.
In theory, this is possible.
In companies, administrators often have the opportunity to read e-mail.
Law enforcement agencies and intelligence agencies also have legal means to intercept or access emails.
This includes possible illegal spying activities.
Is it possible to protect emails from reading?
With encryption according to the OpenPGP standard, an email can be effectively encrypted against reading.
With high technical effort, it is also possible to hide the metadata of an e-mail communication, so that it is not even possible to recognize without delay who communicated with whom.
How important are Yahoo and Google in the email market?
In the mainly privately used mailboxes, Yahoo and Google play only a subordinate role, according to a study conducted by Convios Consulting in August 2013.
While the shares of Yahoo Mail had last fallen, Gmail from Google was able to increase significantly.
