Actually no story.
And one that has already come so in the years that it already looks like a fossil: the first time I heard the “independence means passport control” phrase at least 40 years ago.
An interesting point is lost in the constant repetition of this ancient history.
Why should one expect an independent Scotland to dance after the European pipe?
Why exchange the yoke of London for that of Brussels, especially now?
These are the real European news: the great post-war plan for the unification of Europe has stalled.
With the crisis of the euro, the project Europe has officially died.
Everywhere in the EU, parties who are hostile to the EU or want to throw the euro as a common currency overboard are gaining ground.
Even in Germany, the eurosceptic party Alternative for Germany – founded only this year – was able to raise almost five million votes in the Bundestag elections in September and thus effectively expel the Free Democrats (the equivalent of the British Liberal Democrats) from the Bundestag.
There has always been domestic resistance to the plan to create a federalist Europe.
The current economic crisis is a turning point.
Because of the strict austerity policy imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank in conjunction with the compulsory jacket into which the respective national economies are forced by adhering to the common currency, many people believe that the project Europe has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with the fact that national governments are causing excessive budget deficits – this was only the case in Greece.
Instead, the Eurosystem has fixed its members on exchange rates that are beneficial to German exporters – and German politicians would like to let that happen.
Without the possibility of a devaluation of the local currency, Southern Europe finds itself with a built-in productivity disadvantage over Germany.
The only way is to cut wages and public spending – driven by Berlin.
Behind the current tax and monetary problems lies a deeper European productivity problem.
As a result of the “green” energy directives imposed by Brussels – a code for subsidizing French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers – the European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as much for gas compared to the United States.
This is a paralyzing cost disadvantage, as we have already seen in Grangemouth.
All of the world’s wage regulations do not protect the European petrochemical industry from being pushed into the corner by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, a revolt is stirring up, especially in France, the former cheerleader of the EU.
After the war, the political elite of France saw the EU as a vehicle to keep Germany in check and to raise Paris on par with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a gateway to political legitimacy and has pushed Europe into its own economic policy, with which the stricken French economy has to struggle.
The result: Marine Le Pen’s right-wing, anti-EU Front National has just won a decisive re-election and thus put the ruling Socialists in third place.
The Front National is now the most popular party in France with 24 percent of votes – a timely warning to the UK Labour Party that it cannot assume a split in the right spectrum would automatically mean benefits for the left.
What does Le Pen do with her newly gained popularity among the working-class white French?
She wants to use the EU elections next year to forge an anti-EU, anti-community currency bloc in the European Parliament.
If the anti-EU parties do well in these elections – and that is very possible – then for the first time such a block could dominate the European Parliament.
This is the point to which I want to go: In the not too distant future, the growing resentment against the EU and the single currency will come together for the abolition of the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will rather become something like the “Europe of (sovereign) nations” favoured by General de Gaulle.
Germany and some of its satellite economies may stick to the euro, but France and Southern Europe will return to their own currencies.
I expect Britain to distance itself from this project in the hope of cuddling with the United States.
However, Washington’s growing interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will stand alone in the Atlantic rain.
Where is Scotland in all this?
We can choose to be a region of (in the last consequence) Little England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests – which also includes telling Berlin and Brussels what they can hide.
I suspect that Scotland could do well in a looser European union if we retain our own currency.
Cooperation with other like-minded countries is easier in a non-federated Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should consider equalizing it to Norway and retaining our economic independence.
The SNP government in Scotland is – remarkably – the most successful political movement against austerity in Europe and won a spectacular majority in 2011 due to the rejection of the proposed (and carried out) cuts blamed on Labour Finance Minister Alistair Darling and the subsequent Tory-Lib Dem coalition.
It would be ridiculous for Scotland to opt for independence now, only to get an austerity policy imposed by Berlin and Brussels.
Early Puberty: Growing up faster
African American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty more likely than their white peers, research shows.
Physical changes do not mean puberty.
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are responsible
Experts believe epidemic obesity is a trigger of early puberty
The trend towards early puberty is less pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in child health and family issues.
Should a mother be worried if her daughter grows breasts and sham hair at the age of seven or eight?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these early physical changes are relatively normal among American girls and represent a new norm.
“I spend a lot of time reassuring parents – usually this is not a sign that puberty is coming soon,” Kaplowitz explained.
Obvious signs of development, such as growing breasts, sham and arm hair, as well as body odor, appear earlier in girls.
Nevertheless, there has been only a slight shift in the age of menarca (the onset of the first menstrual bleeding) over the last 40 years.
In the United States, the average age is 12.5 years, slightly less than 12.75 in 1970.
“When the development of the breasts begins, it will take at least two to three years until the menarche,” said Kaplowitz, also author of the book “Early Puberty in Girls: The Essential Guide to Dealing with This Common Problem.”
Time is the most accurate test of how puberty progresses.
It is controversial what actually represents the beginning of puberty, but it is considered “early maturity” when breast enlargement is accompanied by a growth boost before the age of eight.
In most cases, the process slows down or stagnates – something a pediatrician can closely monitor.
With faster progress, tests by an endocrinologist may be indicated to rule out serious problems such as tumors or cysts.
There are treatments to delay early menstruation and prevent another consequence: premature bone aging, which can ultimately lead to growth inhibition and thus small body growth in adults.
Recommendations for drug or hormone therapy are based on the age of the child, development rate, growth rate and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is restrained about drugs, but he admits, “Suppressing puberty can mitigate behavioral problems and the feelings of girls being different from their peers.”
The other big problem is understandable: parents just don’t want their very young daughters to have the period.
“They’re worried about the risk of pregnancy or about how they handle the hygienic side,” Kaplowitz said.
“It was a shock,” remembers a woman whose daughter got her days at ten.
Even though there were first signs and we had talked about menstruation, she was emotionally unprepared.
She came home frightened and excited from school because she was the first in her circle of friends.
There are many widely published theories about the causes of early puberty.
However, there is no conclusive evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media are causative.
Boys come into puberty earlier than girls.
Kaplowitz believes that the most convincing premise is the epidemic of obesity.
He supported conducting a 2001 study on girls aged six to nine that established a link between body fat and entry into puberty.
Other studies support this conclusion, but there are many other factors that played a role.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty more likely than their white peers.
There are different explanations for this.
Globally, early puberty seems to be influenced by all sorts of things, from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another mystery: Although boys grow facial and skull hair earlier, the trend towards a full-fledged earlier puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other doctors at the AAP conference emphasized the complexity of the topic.
The appearance of acne and shy hair is common even in babies and young children.
“We need to be careful how we identify the true onset of puberty,” said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Goryeb Children’s Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to get advice from their pediatrician on how to talk to their child.
“This can mean that you have to have a conversation sooner than expected,” Kaplowitz advised.
If you stay calm, the child usually reacts well.
Girls who bloom early need the assurance that the process is a normal part of life, even if it comes earlier than thought.
