Pension houses boom in Singapore as the crisis has arrived in the middle class
In a pantry at the Bendemeer shopping center in Singapore, Janani Amirthalinga exchanges a golden bracelet, a ring and a pair of earrings to pay for her daughters’ school fees.
“My husband and I just bought a house, there’s all my money,” says Amirthalinga.
Although she earns $3,000 a month as an administrative employee and her husband is also working, the monthly family income is not enough, she explains.
In fact, demand in parts of Southeast Asia – where household debt is increasing – is so high that ValueMax, where it made its exchange, became the third hedge house listed on the Singapore Stock Exchange this week.
The pledge of jewelry is not only a quick way to get money – $1,300 in the case of Janani Amirthalinga – but also almost as inexpensive as an unsecured bank loan.
Typically, deposit houses in Singapore require an effective annual interest rate of 17 percent, which is just above the 15.4 percent that the United Overseas Bank demands from a local lender with a branch in the same shopping center.
But mortgages offer the advantage that there is no credit check or proof of income required here, which is why loans are possible faster than with banks.
This is why millions of people in the region turn to mortgages after families feel the pressure of rising living costs and increasing household and consumer debt.
After five years of robust growth since the global financial crisis and cheap loans due to a looser fiscal policy in the developed economies, lower- and middle-income families are looking for mortgages to offset the gap in a staggering economy.
This week, the rating agency Standard & Poor's described rising household debt, mainly due to rising mortgages, as a risk factor for the creditworthiness of Asian banks.
Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore have the highest domestic debt ratio to GDP in Asia, according to the agency.
Malaysia is at the top of the list with 80 percent of GDP, an increase of 60 percent in 2008.
Economists are also concerned about the high consumer debt in Thailand, which just got out of a technical recession this week.
On Thursday, the data showed a continued weakness in exports and a decline in consumer demand.
“In the end, this means that in the face of rising costs, people in the middle to lower segments (income scale) will try to supplement their income wherever possible,” said Song Seng Wun, an economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
Historic highs in gold prices over the past two years have further reinforced the tendency to pledge personal belongings as people take advantage of the opportunity to convert family jewelry into cash.
In Singapore, about 70 percent of the pledged items in the city state’s 200 pledges are gold.
People say to themselves, “The price of gold looks good, let’s pledge grandmother’s gold chain and get it back next month.”
Thailand’s largest mortgage operator, EasyMoney, has seen a 20-percent customer growth in its stores in recent months.
The growth in the mortgage business is so strong that ValueMax, which operates its subsidiaries in Bendemeer and 15 more in Singapore, wants to expand not only to neighboring Malaysia – where the company operates four houses – but also outside Asia, says Yeah Lee Ching, Managing Director of ValueMax.
The company funds it with 60 percent of the $66 million Singapore dollar it raised this week with its opening in Singapore.
While some lenders have fallen into the crossfire because of high interest rates, Yeah explains that mortgages not only offer cheaper interest rates than other lenders, but also did not directly increase debt.
“Customers borrow items they already own, and liquidating personal valuables does not increase household education,” she explains.
The business of collateral loans is increasingly accepted by society as a short-term, secured financing.
Also, not all people who use mortgages are in financial difficulties.
Rich people from Singapore also come to ValueMax’s stores to pledge gold bars and Rolex watches, for which they get up to 60 percent of the purchase price in cash.
Customers come from every social layer.
“These include wealthy people who borrow something for a business or investment in the short term, or small who need to bridge gaps in cash flow,” Yeah says.
Sometimes you just need money very quickly.
