Rescue Package Over 325 Million Australian Dollars for Tasmanian Healthcare
The Australian government insists on the tough conditions associated with the $325 million Australian bailout package for Tasmanian healthcare to ensure that the state government can’t waste the money.
Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek has announced that the Commonwealth will take "immediate action" to avoid a crisis caused by the island's aging population, a higher rate of chronic diseases and systemic impairments.
The funding for a four-year period was decided after government consultations with the independent Tasmanian MP Andrew Wilkie.
“The government has drawn up an emergency rescue package that we believe addresses the unique challenges facing the state,” Plibersek said today.
The $325 million package includes $31 million in emergency aid for election services.
Another 2,600 surgeries, including orthopedic procedures and treatment for gray star, are aimed at removing residues.
In addition, there is funding for day clinics in Hobart and Launceston, better post-patient care, specialist medical training, mental health services, and the introduction of a system for electronic recording of health data in local hospitals.
“These investments are in line with the ideas concerned clinical staff have told me that they are the best way to improve the Tasmanian health system,” said Tanya Plibersek.
The Minister insisted on a strict reporting and accountability obligation of the Tasmanian government.
The state would have to maintain the current level of funding in order to receive money from the Commonwealth and report monthly where the additional funds were spent.
A three-member commission will be set up to ensure that the state provides health services as effectively and efficiently as possible.
As Wilkie explained today, the $325 million would be of little use if “they were not accompanied by real reforms that would bring the Tasmanian public health system to a more sustainable course.”
Nevertheless, he praised the government for responding to his request for urgent assistance, which he first expressed to the prime minister in early May.
“I am confident that federal aid will make a big contribution to removing the state’s public health system from the list of concerns,” Wilkie said.
According to the state government, these election outcomes will largely compete with recent cuts.
But the opposition’s health policy spokesman at the federal level, Peter Dutton, is of the opinion that today’s announcement is just a “plaster solution.”
"We are in the present situation because the laboratory state government has withdrawn $430 million from the health system," he told ABC TV.
It can’t be that a state government pulls almost half a billion dollars out of the system and the Commonwealth puts 300 million into it and then pretends it’s good news.
Dutton urged Plibersek to guarantee that not a single dollar of the bailout package will be spent on additional bureaucracy.
