Syria has destroyed its ability to produce chemical weapons, according to a surveillance group
Syria has destroyed key chemical weapons manufacturing facilities and poison gas ammunition, the global chemical weapons surveillance group said on Thursday, as severe clashes occurred in the north of the country near one of the sites where presumed toxic substances are stored.
Also on Thursday, a group of Syrian activists announced that more than 120,000 people have been killed almost three years ago since the beginning of the civil war.
The announcement by the Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (OPCW) came a day before the date of the meeting.
November 1, which the Hague-based organization Damascus had set to destroy or make “inoperable” all facilities for the manufacture of chemical weapons, including all machinery for mixing chemicals into poisonous gas and filling ammunition.
The completion of this process, which essentially represents the first stage of destruction, is an important milestone in an ambitious timetable aimed at destroying all Syrian chemical weapons by mid-2014.
The destruction of the facilities means that Syria can no longer produce new chemical weapons.
However, Damascus still has to begin to destroy the existing weapons and supplies.
It is estimated that there are about 1,000 tons of chemicals and weapons in the country, including mustard gas and the nerve gas sarin.
The announcement came at a time when fighting took place in the city of Safira on Thursday, where experts say there is a chemical weapons production facility and warehouses, the British-based Syrian Observatory for Human Rights said.
The activist group, which tracks the death toll in Syria through a network of activists, said on Thursday that 120,296 people have died.
Among them, 61,067 are civilians, including 6,365 children.
On the government side, 29,954 of them belonged to President Bashar Assad’s army, 18,678 were government-friendly fighters and 187 were Lebanese Hezbollah militias.
Also among the dead are 2,202 deserted army soldiers and 5,375 opposition fighters, many of them foreigners.
On July 25, the UN estimated the death toll in this conflict since March 2011 at 100,000.
This number has not yet been updated.
The conflict has forced about two million people to flee the country.
Assad’s troops have been fighting in Safira for weeks against the rebels, many of whom have links to al-Qaeda groups.
The Observatory said there were losses on both sides on Thursday, but did not give any details.
The fighting underscores the danger faced by the chemical weapons inspectors as their mission to liberate Syria from its poisonous weapons arsenal is a race against time amidst a tumultuous civil war.
According to OPCW, which works closely with the United Nations, the team “is now convinced that it has seen and witnessed the destruction of all of Syria’s key production and mixing facilities.”
Therefore, “no further inspection activities are currently planned.”
Earlier this week, the inspectors said they had completed the first round of inspections and visited 21 of the 23 sites indicated by Damascus.
Due to security concerns, the visit to two facilities was not possible, the inspectors said.
On Thursday, the OPWC said the two sites had been “abandoned ... and the objects of the chemical weapons program there have been moved to other mentioned facilities that have been inspected.”
It was not immediately clear whether the site in Safira was one of the two facilities that OPCW inspectors could not visit.
Syria has submitted a plan for the complete destruction of its chemical weapons, which must be approved by the OPWC Executive Committee next month.
“I take the hat for the courage and courage you have all shown in fulfilling the most challenging mission this organization has ever carried out,” said Ahmed Uzumcu, the monitoring organization’s general director, in a comment published by OPCW.
For three years now, the predominantly Sunni Muslim rebels have been fighting in this civil war against the Assad government and its security forces, many of whom are members of the Alawites, to separate Shia Islam.
In view of further developments, the head of the observation group, Rami Abdurrahman, said there was a strong explosion in an air defense facility in the Syrian coastal province of Latakia on Wednesday.
The cause of the explosion is unknown, he said.
Judgment for Bali bombers
Survivors and relatives of the 202 people who were killed in the 2002 Bali bomb attack reacted indignantly to the verdict for the last of the instigators brought to court, as Umar Patek, in their opinion, should be shot by law.
Patek, who was on the run for a decade as one of Southeast Asia's most wanted individuals, was sentenced to 20 years in prison yesterday for his role in building explosives for the bombing.
He could be released after 15 years.
The 45-year-old was found guilty of the mass murder in connection with the attack on two nightclubs in the popular tourist district of Kuta, which killed 202 people, including 88 Australians, and wounded many more.
A conviction was also made in a series of terrorism-related charges, including a wave of explosive attacks on churches in Indonesia on Christmas Eve in 2000.
The prosecutor’s office had demanded life imprisonment, even though it could have requested the death penalty for the man, also referred to as “Demolition Man” because of his reputation as a master bombmaker.
The decision has raised painful memories in June Corteen, a mother from Perth who lost her 39-year-old twins Jane and Jenny in the devastation caused by Patek and his co-conspirators a decade ago.
Struggling with tears, she said Patek should have been sentenced to death.
I really mean he should follow in the footsteps of the other guys.
“You should put him in front of a shooting command,” Corteen told AAP.
I have to live every day with the feeling that I will never have any more grandchildren and I will never see my daughters again.
The Sari Club was grounded when, on October 12, 2002, a massive bomb exploded in a small loader parked in front of the nightclub shortly after 23:00.
Peter Hughes was in Paddy's Bar, where only 20 seconds earlier a suicide bomber detonated a backpack filled with explosives.
He fell into a coma for a month after the attack and “died” three times while hanging on a life support system.
Hughes said Patek deserved the same fate as the three other members of the Jemaah Islamiah terror cell – Amrozi, Mukhlas and Imam Samudra – who were responsible for the massacre and were executed four years ago.
Indeed, this guy should get the death penalty first of all.
To leave him alive – no, there is no reason to leave him alive.
Getting 20 years after he killed 202 people and wounded many hundreds is not much.
Patek is the last Bali bomber to face trial.
He escaped a decade of arrest, but was eventually arrested in January 2011 in the Pakistani city of Abbottabad, where U.S. forces killed former al-Qaeda leader Osama bin Laden just four months later.
During the hearing, an FBI agent said intelligence reports had indicated that Patek was in Pakistan to meet bin Laden with the aim of rebuilding the link between Southeast Asian terrorist groups and al-Qaeda.
“He didn’t stand,” Corteen said.
Until recently, he had shown no regret for how much suffering he had done to other people.
The verdict came before the 10th anniversary of the attack this year, which is committed with commemorative celebrations in Bali and Australia.
“There will be a lot of tears this year,” Corteen said.
