FAA: Passengers can now use electronic devices on planes (but not make mobile calls)
Air travelers can now use their electronic devices from departure to landing to read, work, play, music, and watch movies, but not make phone calls, according to new guidelines issued by the U.S. Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) on Thursday.
However, passengers should not expect these changes to be implemented immediately.
How quickly they will be implemented will depend on the respective airline, FAA employee Michael Huerta said at a news conference.
Airlines must prove to the FAA that aircraft comply with the new guidelines and that they have updated flight personnel training manuals and equipment storage regulations in accordance with the new regulations.
The FAA said it has already received plans from some airlines that want to expand the use of portable electronic devices in aircraft.
These airlines included Delta and JetBlue.
“Depending on the state of the plan, we could approve the extended use of electronic devices very soon,” the FAA said in a statement.
Currently, passengers have to turn off smartphones, tablets and other devices when the aircraft doors are closed.
They are only allowed to restart them when the aircraft has reached a height of three kilometers and the captain gives the green light.
When entering the landing flight, passengers must turn them off again and may not start again before the aircraft has landed.
Under the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are secure against electronic interference could allow their passengers to use the devices even when taking off, landing, and on the runway, the FAA said.
Most new transport aircraft and other aircraft that have been redesigned to use Wi-Fi at larger altitudes should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the professional flight crew, welcomed the changes.
“If the new regulation is safely implemented – and we are working closely with the airline on this – it will benefit both sides,” Glading said.
We are honestly tired of having to feel like guardians on this subject.
Nevertheless, internet connections for browsing, exchanging emails, text messages or downloading data below three kilometers remained prohibited, the authority explained.
Passengers are asked to put smartphones, tablets and other devices in flight mode.
So still no “Words With Friends,” the scrabble-like online game that actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011 when he publicly had to leave an American Airlines jet because he refused to turn off the device while the plane was parked on the flight deck.
And heavier devices such as laptops will still need to be stored, as there is a risk of injury if they fly through the cabin.
Mobile phones during the flight are also prohibited.
The regulatory authority for telephone calls lies with the Federal Communications Commission (FCC), not the FAA.
FAA may lift ban on certain electronic devices at takeoff and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, a national transportation safety expert, told CBS News that phones would still be considered a risk.
“Mobile phones are really a problem, not just because they could potentially cause interference to navigation devices, but because we know from the FCC that airborne transmission can also interfere with broadcasters,” Rosenker said.
A industry advisory committee set up by the FAA to investigate this issue last month recommended that the government allow for wider use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, pressure on the FAA has increased to loosen restrictions on use.
Critics such as Democratic Senator Claire McCaskill from Missouri have argued that there are no valid security reasons for the ban.
The restrictions are also becoming increasingly difficult to enforce because the use of the devices has become ubiquitous.
In some studies, it is said that up to one-third of passengers forget to turn off the device or ignore it.
The FAA began restricting the use of electronic devices by air travelers in 1966, after reports of interference of navigation and communication devices by passenger-powered UKW radios became known, which represented the latest technology trend at the time.
New aircraft are far more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed and approved by the FAA to avoid electronic interference.
Airlines have been offering passengers Wi-Fi for a few years when the altitude is reached.
The aircraft adapted to Wi-Fi systems are also less sensitive to interference.
The vast majority of passenger aircraft should be suitable for the stronger use of electronic devices under the new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today’s electronic devices generally emit significantly less radio radiation than previous generations.
E-reader, for example, only emits minimal radiation when you switch.
However, when downloading or sending data, the transfer values are stronger.
Among the advocates of easing the restrictions on the use of devices by passengers is Amazon.com.
In 2011, company employees called a passenger plane full of Kindle e-reader and made a test flight to identify problems, but could not find any.
Members of the FAA Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings about the risks associated with the use of devices.
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Airline Passengers said he believes the failure caused by the devices is real, even though the risk is minimal.
Other committee members said there are only isolated reports of pilots speaking in favour of interference with aircraft systems through the devices, and most of them are very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to order passengers to turn off the devices when instruments land in poor visibility conditions.
A group from the travel industry welcomed the changes and described them as a reasonable adaptation for travelers who would now be fully equipped with technology.
“We are pleased that the FAA recognizes that a pleasant passenger experience is not in conflict with safety,” said Roger Dow, CEO of the U.S. Travel Association.
