Is Europe’s elite ready to do business with Britain?
Business for Britain was launched in April with the intention of bringing the economy to the table and defining what those who provide wealth and work in the UK want to change in our relations with the EU.
For this purpose, we commissioned the largest and most comprehensive survey among UK business leaders and asked them what they think about the UK, the economy and the EU.
YouGov surveyed more than 1,000 business executives depicting UK corporate sizes, sectors and regions.
The results of the survey will surprise many.
We found that the vast majority of companies are now exporting outside Europe, focusing on countries that are modernising and growing, while countries in the EU are stagnant.
They want the government to favor new trade ties with countries such as China, India and Brazil instead of stopping the long and exhausting process of reforming the obscure EU institutions.
When asked for their views on certain regulated issues – from cartel law to product legislation – the majority of business leaders are of the opinion that control over these key competences should be returned to Westminster.
There was widespread dissatisfaction with the single market, as companies said the cost of Brussels regulations would now outweigh the benefits of being part of the European trade area – even 40 percent of large companies agreed to the one that is traditionally most European-friendly.
Finally, and that probably says the most, our survey of business leaders revealed that a significant majority would like Britain to take a course towards changing the deal and a relationship with the EU based on trade, not politics.
This insight, found in companies of all sizes and leading corporations, shows that the economy is pushing for a “meaningful change” that will bring the handbook of action back to the UK.
A change in the agreement and better conditions for Britain would lead to a change of opinion in favour of staying in the EU in a referendum at 16 percent.
The prime minister should have no doubts: this poll shows that the British economy is behind his plan to renegotiate the British conditions for EU membership.
It also shows that companies expect a clear shift in power relations back to the UK from a renegotiation.
A better deal for the UK economy is possible and increasingly needed as the Eurozone is now moving towards a tighter economic and fiscal union.
Employment and growth in the UK must be the priority, as the results of our survey show, which means increased focus on trade for companies and a fundamental change in Brussels’ approach to regulation.
