Royal Commission Hearing: Two YMCA Employees Accused of Sexual Offences Against Jonathan Lord
Two YMCA employees from New South Wales (NSW) had been charged with child-related sexual offenses before charges against Caringbah’s childcare provider Jonathan Lord were filed in 2011, the Royal Commission on Child Sexual Abuse learned.
However, in the opening statement before the Commission, the YMCA said it had “never had to deal with an incident of sexual abuse of children in the organization.”
Managing Director Phillip Hare was questioned on one case in which one YMCA employee was charged with child pornography offences, and another in which a sports teacher at YMCA Caringbah Hall was convicted in 1991 for abusing children entrusted to him.
Hare told Gail Furness, one of the Commission’s assistant lawyers, that he knew of the first case, but did not know of the second.
He acknowledged that the opening statement of the YMCA to the Commission was also inaccurate in stating that “there were external reviews of the YMCA in which the YMCA was recognized as at the forefront of child safety.”
Instead, evidence before the Commission shows that the YMCA was informed that it received the second lowest rating of four possible in a quality audit by the Department of Education and Communities in August of the year.
Hare, who started at 21 at YMCA, admitted that management failed “from me down” in hiring Lord and failed to ensure that employees were aware of their obligations to report breaches of parental safety guidelines.
Lord was convicted of sexual assault on 12 boys during his two-year YMCA service earlier this year.
He was sentenced to at least six years in prison.
Hare, however, denies that the YMCA had a cultural problem that prevented employees from reporting Lord’s violations of children’s safety.
The staff said they had observed violations, including Lord being alone with children, taking care of her privately as a babysitter, letting her sit on his knee, telling one that he loved it, and letting children play with his phone.
Danielle Ockwell, whose supervisor was Lord and who had asked for training on child protection because she was concerned about his behavior, said that the child care director Jacqui Barnat, who was the supervisor of Lords at YMCA Caringbah, was “very intimidating and most of the time very inaccessible.”
The CEO stated that he would not accept statements from employees that they did not dare to report to their superiors.
Instead, he said, their friendship with Lord had affected their judgment, which is why they would not have it to him.
Hare explained that he communicated to the board of YMCA NSW his view that the lesson the organization has to draw from the “Jonathan-Lord incident” is “not about the reporting” by employees, and the board agreed to him.
Hare said the decision to urge employees to sign secrecy obligations shortly after the allegations appeared was made by YMCA’s Executive Director of Children’s Services, Liam Whitley.
He said it was meant to prevent contamination of evidence, but that it was “excessively” and poorly implemented.
The YMCA NSW was not a safe organization for children when Jonathan Lord was employed there between 2009 and 2011, Professor Stephen Smallbone of Griffith University, an expert on sexual abuse of children, told the commission.
He explained that there were “serious problems” with the recruitment, review, recruitment, training and supervision of employees.
The hearing was postponed until December 20.
