Scientists have been able to shed more light on the connection between a dog’s tail twitching and his mood.
Previous research had shown that happy dogs with their tail waved more to the right (from the dog’s point of view), while nervous dogs were on the left side.
But now scientists say other dogs can perceive these subtle differences and react to them.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trient, said: “It is well known that in humans, the left and right hemispheres of the brain respond differently to stimuli that generate positive or negative emotions.”
Here we have tried to look at this in other species.
He also noted that in dogs, just like in humans, the right half of the brain is responsible for the movement of the left side and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played different roles in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to their peers’ lateral tail swing, the researchers monitored the animals while watching these other dogs’ films.
They measured the heart rate of the four-legged and analyzed the behavior.
Probably we will soon understand why the tail moves in one direction, sometimes in the other.
Professor Vallortigara said, “We showed the dogs movies with dogs – either a true version or a silhouette to eliminate distracting other aspects, and we were able to control the tail’s movement more to the left or right.”
When the animals saw a otherwise expressive dog moving its tail to the right (see from the perspective of the wretched dog), they remained completely relaxed.
But if the tail healing was mostly to the left (again from the perspective of the dog who wedles), their heart rate increased and they looked restless.
According to Professor Vallortigara, the dogs do not intentionally communicate with each other through these movements.
Instead, he is convinced that the dogs learned from experience what movements they should worry about and when not.
He said, “If you have different encounters with other dogs and wagging with your tail in one direction is more associated with friendly behavior and the right side is more likely to produce less friendly behavior, then you react based on those experiences.”
The researchers say the findings could help dog owners, veterinarians and trainers better understand their pet’s emotions.
John Bradshaw, a dog behavior expert and guest fellow at the University of Bristol’s Faculty of Veterinary Medicine, said this was not the first study to examine whether left and right are important for dogs.
Last year, a team from the University of Lincoln found that dogs turn their heads to the left when looking at an aggressive dog, and to the right when it comes to a satisfied dog.
In another study at the University of Victoria in Canada, it was stated that “dogs are more likely to turn to a robot dog when its ‘tail’ swings to the left rather than to the right, instead of becoming upset – exactly the opposite of the Italian study.”
According to him, the differences may be due to the fact that the dogs in the various studies did not interpret the animals in the films or the robot dogs as dogs.
A study of how dogs react to real dogs could help, he explained.
“While there is substantial evidence for many different mammals that the two hemispheres of the brain are used for different purposes, many of the details still need to be determined – and dogs are no exception,” Bradshaw said.
However, since their behavior can simply be recorded, it will probably not take long before we understand why the tail sometimes moves in one direction, sometimes in the other.
