Pope Francis to appoint first cardinals in February
Pope Francis will appoint new cardinals for the first time on February 22, the Vatican announced on Thursday.
Cardinals are the highest-ranking clerics in the Catholic Church after the Pope, and they are also the ones who elect a Pope, so Francis will thereby appoint the first group of men who will ultimately participate in the election of his successor.
Currently there are 201 cardinals.
However, a cardinal who has reached the age of 80 can no longer participate in the papal election – this falls to a group of 120 “elected cardinals”.
In a statement announcing the news, Father Federico Lombardi, a spokesman for the Vatican, said there will be a meeting of all cardinals before the ceremony for the appointment of the new cardinals, also known as the Consistory, will take place.
“Pope Francis has decided to announce his decision to convene the Consistory in February in advance so that other meetings that require the participation of cardinals from all over the world can be planned,” Lombardi said.
Jack Valero of Catholic Voices said the number of eligible cardinals is likely to have dropped by February.
He explained that a pope would normally appoint as many cardinals as needed to get the number of eligible cardinals back to 120, and as many cardinals over 80 as he would like.
The consistory next year is therefore significant because it will be the first since the election of Francis in March this year, Valero said.
Currently, there is a certain overlap on the part of Europe and especially Italy.
“It will be interesting to see if the new pope will appoint cardinals from the rest of the world to restore balance,” he said.
Forty percent of Catholics live in South America, but they have only a small number of cardinals.
The cardinals will also be the first to be called since the formation of the Council of Cardinals founded by Francis, a group of eight cardinals from around the world who are tasked with finding ways to reform the Church.
In the past, the Pope decided everything on his own.
“Now Francis has chosen these eight cardinals to help him,” Valero said.
He said it was “very possible” that Francis would ask the cardinals for advice.
But we haven’t been in this situation until now – it’s all new.
Valero said that typically bishops from large places are called to be cardinals, but Francis is “filled with surprises – so we don’t know who he is appointing.”
