Desperate scream of an Obama voter
I have elected President Obama twice in the hope that change is possible.
He says Obama has made praiseworthy efforts that have been thwarted by Republican blockade tactics.
Blockade policy doesn’t excuse Obamacare’s website problems, the drone attacks
Obama’s memoirs of the 2008 election campaign are a sad reminder of what would have been possible
Nathaniel P. Morris is a second year student at Harvard Medical School.
I am currently reading a very sad book.
It’s a book I thought would excite me during the sad second year of my medical school and give me hope again.
It’s called “The Audacity to Win” and depicts Barack Obama’s memoirs of the 2008 presidential election.
When I finish with my patient subtitles in the evening and go to bed, the book takes me back to a time when politics inspired millions and could take the breath of a speech.
The election became a landslide victory and news speakers stopped to highlight the historical significance of this hour.
My classmates cried out of joy and my parents collected all the newspapers they could find.
A young team of visionaries was on their way to the White House and the nation was ready for change.
When Obama took office in 2008, he had 82% of the votes.
Then I close the book.
Switching back to the present is an evil awakening, like being ripped out of a dream.
It’s hard to remember those optimistic times – they seem to be a vague memory, a sad reminder of missed opportunities.
In the years since I first voted, something has actually changed.
But it is simply nothing I could have imagined.
I recognize the great and versatile things that Obama has achieved, from the passing of the Affordable Care Act for health insurance to the military withdrawal from Iraq, the end of the forced concealment of homosexuality in the army and the killing of Osama bin Laden.
I also think that the party-political blockade tactic has driven too many efforts to advance our nation: immigration reform, a public option for health insurance, and the closure of Guantanamo Bay, to name a few.
But after defending the Obama administration against colleagues and acquaintances countless times, I have come to an end with my attempts to explain it.
I have reached a point of political despair.
The Republican blockade policy cannot explain why one allows the interrogation of foreign heads of state or the killing of innocent children by drones overseas.
It cannot explain why the National Security Agency collects data on the privacy of Americans and why whistleblowers who disclose government misconduct are punished.
It cannot explain why Anwar al-Awlaki, a U.S. citizen, was murdered without trial, nor why public funding and spending limits were bypassed during the presidential election.
It doesn’t justify the findings of a report that says the White House’s efforts to calm the media are “the most aggressive ... since the Nixon administration.”
And most recently, it can’t excuse the inability to design a simple website for the more than three years since the Affordable Care Act was passed.
I don’t know if that’s what I should have expected.
Whether I should have understood at the age of 18 that the government’s work could contradict its predecessor political campaigns.
Obviously, the House of Representatives is not a predictable course as an opposition party and random events like the Newtown Massacre shape the public debate.
But when I look at the above examples, it seems that they are largely chosen by the government itself.
That disturbs me the most.
I re-elected Obama in 2012 not because I was enthusiastic about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney represented a confusing and untouched alternative, he seemed unable to set his direction and positions.
I had the impression that a second term for Obama, free from the pressure of upcoming elections, would fulfill the hope we had heard of so long ago.
But with the approval rates for Obama falling below 45% this week, the return to 2008 through this book has become even harder.
It arouses in me the longing for the many promises that have broken up in the air.
This week I read a section in the book describing how Obama suffered a heavy loss against Clinton in the Pennsylvania presidential election.
In a meeting with the electoral assistants after the decision, he told his employees that they would have to come back on course and follow the purpose of their cause.
“I want us to find our magic,” he said.
We need to remember who we are.
It’s five years later, Mr. President, and I couldn’t agree more strongly with you.
