Dr. Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers performed 700 free surgeries last year.
He became a doctor himself and works as a vascular surgeon at the Central Hospital in Yaoundé.
He also founded a non-profit organization called ASCOVIME, which travels to rural areas on weekends and offers free medical care there.
Since 2008, he and his volunteer group have helped 32,000 people.
Nearly every Friday, he and up to 30 people force themselves into minibuses and drive over unfortified terrain to the villages in need of help with the encircled medical equipment on the roof.
Not always everything goes smoothly.
More than once, they had to push their vehicles through rivers and mud.
But when they arrive, they will be received like heroes: a feast, singing and dancing and the best accommodation the place has to offer.
In these villages, free medical care is really a reason to celebrate, and Bwelle – with his wide smile and boundless energy – is happy to be there for the joyful celebration.
The next morning, the team then starts examining hundreds of patients.
“We treat 500 people per trip,” says Bwelle.
They come from a range of 60 kilometers around the village – and that on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics offers medical care in a number of areas.
Many people are treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others get crows, donated glasses, or free birth certificates – a document required for school, but many poor families simply can’t afford.
In the evening, the team performs simple operations with local anesthesia.
The operations usually take place in a school, town hall or apartment; after the procedure, the patients get up and go to the rest area to make room for the neighbor.
The lighting for the OP and disinfection equipment is powered by the group’s generator and so Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early hours of Sunday morning.
It’s an exhausting curriculum, but the village musicians usually help keep the team motivated.
“They drum all night so we can stay awake and continue our work,” says Bwelle.
On Sunday, the team then returns to the city, tired but proud of the work done.
The group – a mixture of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students – has performed 700 free surgeries over the past year and knows that their work is making a huge difference for the people they help.
One man explained that the free surgery of a spleen fracture he received now allows him to work again.
“This will change the future of my family,” the man said.
In addition to the weekend clinics and his work as a surgeon in the hospital, Bwelle also works at night in private clinics in Yaoundé.
With this second job he finances 60% of his non-profit activity, according to Bwelle; the rest comes from private donations.
“I really don’t know when he’s sleeping,” says Katie O’Malley, who studies medicine at Drexel University in Philadelphia in her second year and volunteers for Bwelle’s group.
He’s always either in the hospital or trying to raise money for the organization so he can go on those campaigns.
For medical and nursing students like O’Malley, who come from the U.S. and Europe and support Bwelle, this is an opportunity to gain hands-on experience they would never get at home.
“We can be involved in surgeries where we help drain blood or keep the instruments for Dr. Bwelle,” O’Malley explains.
This would never be possible in America as a second year medical student.
Students usually pay for their trip to Cameroon themselves and often bring donated sanitary supplies.
Once they are in Yaoundé, Bwelle takes over accommodation, transportation and guidance.
“He is undoubtedly a hero,” O’Malley said.
He dedicates his life to this organization and his desire to help the Cameroonian people knows no boundaries.
For Bwelle, almost constant work is not a burden.
Helping others to live a happier life and thus fulfilling a promise he gave to his Father brings him great joy.
“I’m so happy when I do this job,” says Bwelle.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I do.
I do it to make people laugh again and to relieve the pain.
Visit the ASCOVIME website and find out how you can help.
