Tourism: descent to the Romans
At about 120 meters in length, a sewage canal from the Roman era is preserved beneath Cologne.
Those who visit Cologne do not pass by the cathedral.
The two towers are about 157 meters high, making it the second tallest church building in Europe.
However, few visitors who admire the two filigrane church towers know that there is also a lot to discover beneath the cathedral.
Rainer Schulze is an expert on the Cologne Underground.
The meeting point for his guided tours is the service center of Cologne-Tourismus directly on the Cathedral.
The tour begins quite unspectacularly: “We start in the underground garage,” says Schulze.
In the 1970s, the city fathers wanted a car-right city, and therefore, from the remains of the old city wall, only what was not too large remained.
Most users of the parking lot are therefore rushing past the Roman remains today and just parking their car.
But if you look closer, you will discover an archaeological site separated by metal grid bars on the park deck D2.
You can see roughly five meters high ruins of hand-sized stones.
"These are the remains of the Roman city wall, which was built in the second half of the first century after Christ," Schulze says.
Before it goes back to daylight, Schulze lets the participants on the upper floor of the park take a look into a dark, 15 meters deep shale.
This is the well of the old dome, which unfortunately is hardly noticed.
The next stop of the tour is the pretorium, and here the participants climb back down into the depth.
Here we see the seat of the once most powerful man north of the Alps, the pretor of the CCAA.
What CCAA means, a visitor would like to know.
The abbreviation stands for "Colonia Claudia Ara Agrippinensium", which in good German means "City of Roman right and City of the Agrippinians, founded under Emperor Claudius at the site of the altar for the emperor cult".
And the pretorium is the former governor's palace, the power centre of the Roman Empire on the Rhine.
From the lobby of the exhibition, a tunnel access leads to the Roman sewage canal, which isined here at about 120 meters in length.
“You can walk a bit along the so-called Cloaca Maxima if you want,” Schulze pleases the guests.
There is a surprise for Schultz.
After picking up the key at the treasury, he leads the group to a 16 meter deep, walkable shade.
“We are now in the Mikwe, a ritual Jewish bath,” he explains.
The Jewish community built their bath deep into the ground to get to the groundwater, which was indispensable for the ritual washings.
To this day, in the lower end of the Mikwe, whose origins date back to the eighth century, different water levels can be read by changing levels of the Rhine.
The Mikwe will be part of an archaeological zone on the Town Hall Square, for which construction works are expected to begin soon.
However, there will be a few years until completion.
