Jerusalem Government Not Confirming Attack on Syrian Air Base
A U.S. government official who wanted to remain anonymous told CNN on Thursday that Israeli fighter jets had attacked an air base in Latakia, Syria, a day earlier.
The targets were "missiles and related equipment" that the Israeli government feared were intended for Lebanese Hezbollah, according to CNN.
Syrian and Lebanese media, as well as the Arab broadcaster Al-Arabiya, had previously that the base in the port city of Latakia was shot in the night of Wednesday to Thursday, and blamed the Israelis for it.
Israeli television channel Channel 2 showed satellite images of the base in Latakia, which showed Russian defense missiles of the type S-125 Newa, as well as a battery of SA-3 missiles, which according to Channel 2 have a range of 35 kilometers and can carry explosive heads up to 70 kilograms.
The government in Jerusalem has not officially confirmed the attack.
However, Reuters quoted a similarly anonymous Israeli government official as saying he believes Israel carried out the attack, but is not sure.
A spokesman for the Israeli Defense Ministry said: “We are not commenting on these reports.”
Journalist Ron Ben-Yishai stressed in the daily newspaper Yedioth Ahronoth that the Syrian regime had previously tried to deliver ground-to-air missiles to Hezbollah.
The Israeli government has repeatedly warned that any attempt by Syria to supply Hezbollah with chemical or other dangerous weapons would mean crossing a “red line” followed by a military response.
John Kerry says in an unprecedented admission that U.S. espionage has gone “unreasonably far too far”
With an unexpected acknowledgment, John Kerry pointed to a weakening of the U.S. deterrent on its surveillance programs, saying that in certain cases, espionage has "goed inappropriately too far."
The Secretary of State also admitted that he and Barack Obama were responsible for switching to “autopilot” when the explosive revelations by whistleblower Edward Snowden about the NSA’s espionage activities became public.
The leaked information has plunged the U.S. government into a diplomatic storm of indignation from its allies.
In a video-transmitted speech at the Open Government conference in London, Kerry said: “Without a doubt, the president and I, as well as others in the government, have heard of some things that have gone by quasi-autopilot, simply because the ability to do this was back to the Second World War and the difficult years of the Cold War, and of course to September 11.”
He later acknowledged as the first senior member of the U.S. government that U.S. espionage has crossed a border, but also stressed that no rights have been abused.
He said, “In some cases, this has gone too far inappropriately.”
The president is determined to provide clarity and is therefore conducting a thorough investigation so that no one needs to feel that abuse is taking place here.
I assure you that the rights of innocent people will not be compromised in this process.
Kerry, however, insisted that the NSA was a force of good and that its surveillance operations had saved many lives.
He added, “We are dealing with a new world where people are ready to blow themselves up.”
There is radical extremism in the world that is aimed at killing people, blowing up, and attacking governments.
So what if you were able to catch it and stop it before it happens?
We have actually prevented aircraft crashes, attacks on buildings and the killing of people because we have learned in advance of such plans.
Meanwhile, U.S. lawmakers will travel to Europe to dispel concerns about alleged U.S. espionage and convince Europeans of the need to continue working with the U.S. in anti-terrorism efforts, the chairman of the Senate Committee on European Affairs said on Thursday.
Senator Chris Murphy of Connecticut said he spoke with representatives of the European Parliament and other individuals this week and was concerned about their threats to stop participating in anti-terror organizations due to frustration over surveillance by the National Security Agency.
“It is very important for the national security interests of the United States that Europeans stay on board in our joint efforts against terrorism,” Murphy, who sits in the Senate for the first time as a Democrat and is chairman of the Senate Committee on Foreign Relations and European Affairs, said in an interview in Washington.
I also go to Europe to make it clear that we must continue to work together in the fight against terrorism, despite their anger over the NSA programs.
Media reports that the NSA has captured millions of telephone data in Europe have burdened relations with some U.S. allies, although the head of the intelligence service said this week that the reports were inaccurate and were based on a misunderstanding of the metadata collected by NATO allies and exchanged with the United States.
Other revelations cited documents disclosed by Snowden that the NSA has monitored the phone of Chancellor Angela Merkel and up to 34 other heads of state worldwide.
The head of national intelligence, James Clapper, defended spying on allies as necessary and stated that this is common on both sides.
In all the tumult, Murphy said his authority was preparing for the congressional trip to take place this year, and hoped that the delegation would include members from both parties and chambers.
The names of the other members will be published in the coming days.
He said the exact route is still being prepared.
While Murphy emphasized that the purpose of the trip was to improve relationships, he also spoke that there would be some “serious words.”
He said European governments should be honest with their people about the kind of espionage programs they have been using for years.
"While we can change our surveillance programs to better protect the rights of Europeans, they must also deal with the fact that we are not the only ones who spy," Murphy said.
Meanwhile, Kerry is scheduled to travel to the Middle East and Poland over the weekend to deal with the resentment of the US strategy in Syria, Egypt and Iran, as well as the US surveillance activities.
