Australian woman appeals prison sentence in Thailand
A 21-year-old woman from Sydney, who was sentenced to 15 days in prison in Phuket for falsely claiming to have been raped by a taxi driver, appealed the verdict and was released on bail.
Stevie Rochelle Bamford was initially found guilty by a provincial court in Phuket on June 15 for making a false testimony after reporting to Thai police that a local taxi driver raped her in the morning hours of Sunday, June 10, while two other men detained her.
Later, however, footage from a video camera showed that she had safely arrived at her hotel after being separated from her Australian friend.
Phuket police interrogated Bamford for two days until they admitted to having invented the story.
Until the trial she was in police custody.
Bamford was sentenced to a 15-day prison sentence in a low-security detention facility on the outskirts of Phuket, rather than in an adult female prison.
She is the daughter of Peter Tunks, a former Australian Rubgy League player who turned to the Foreign Ministry in Canberra to ask for help for his daughter.
Tunks told the Sunday Telegraph in Sydney that the whole family was “extremely concerned” about his daughter’s well-being and wanted her back to Australia.
“Of course, we are very concerned, but we hope she is back home as soon as possible,” Tunks said.
Bamford appealed the judgment and is on free ground against a deposit of 50,000 baht.
In Australian reports it was read that in the meantime she is on vacation in the resort of Krabi in southern Thailand.
The court said Bamford was represented by a local lawyer in Phuket and was warned that the appeal could also result in a higher sentence of up to two years in an adult prison.
However, it is also possible that Thailand, after the recent assassination of travel agent Michelle Smith in Phuket, may have been trying to improve its damaged tourist image and therefore come to an acquittal.
